ormative state‚Äì the one you said ‚Äúis part of the viable america the america that is connected to its own economy where there is a plausible future for the people born into it‚Äù‚Äîand the prerogative state‚Äîwhich has been ‚Äúutterly divorced from‚Äù your normative experience and which has ‚Äúno barbed wire around‚Äù it but ‚Äúmight as well‚Äù perhaps we can say that the ‚Äúbarbed wire‚Äù in this case has a human face and a badge and a whole lot of guns and quite obviously the will to use them but your superficial reading of marx made these ‚Äútwo americas‚Äù out to be a simple consequence of capitalistic greed not a capitalist necessity enforced by the dual state maintained in subjection by the prerogative state are those individuals who make up ‚Äú or  of my country that is no longer necessary to the operation of the economy‚Äù‚Äîalthough it would be wrong to discount the role they play in justifying the very large growth sectors in the economy of law enforcement surveillance and incarceration as a result of this blind spot regarding the dual state you were led to conclude that ‚Äúwe‚Äôve somehow managed to march on to two separate futures‚Äù without really investigating that ‚Äúsomehow‚Äù this quickly made both your reading of history and your beliefs about capitalism problematic when you concluded that american capitalism after world war  was the system that ‚Äúworked the best‚Äù ‚Äúprovided a lot more freedom‚Äù and was extremely successful at ‚Äúcreating mass wealth‚Äù the caveat is that to the extent that we can even say these statements are true they are true only of the normative state and not of the prerogative state let‚Äôs bracket and put aside us foreign policy after world war  which was obsessively dedicated to toppling democratic states all over the world and supporting brutal dictatorships and corrupt cronycapitalist quasidemocratic vassal states in the name of selling ‚Äúthe best product‚Äù even inside the united states the claim that the countr